# Euler Problem: Generate the Theoretical Spectrum of a Linear Peptide

## Problem Description

The theoretical spectrum of a linear peptide is the multiset of all possible subpeptide masses that can be formed by cutting the peptide at various positions. This is a fundamental concept in mass spectrometry and protein analysis.

## Solution in R

```r
# Load required libraries
library(dplyr)

# Define amino acid masses
aa_masses <- list(
  "G" = 57, "A" = 71, "S" = 87, "P" = 97, "V" = 99,
  "T" = 101, "C" = 103, "I" = 113, "L" = 113, "N" = 114,
  "D" = 115, "K" = 128, "Q" = 128, "E" = 129, "M" = 131,
  "H" = 137, "F" = 147, "R" = 156, "Y" = 163, "W" = 186
)

# Function to generate theoretical spectrum of a linear peptide
generate_theoretical_spectrum <- function(peptide) {
  # Convert peptide to character vector
  peptide_chars <- unlist(strsplit(peptide, ""))
  
  # Get masses for each amino acid
  masses <- sapply(peptide_chars, function(aa) aa_masses[[aa]])
  
  # Calculate all possible subpeptide masses
  spectrum <- c(0)  # Start with 0 (empty subpeptide)
  
  # Generate all subpeptides
  n <- length(masses)
  for (i in 1:n) {
    for (j in i:n) {
      # Calculate mass of subpeptide from position i to j
      subpeptide_mass <- sum(masses[i:j])
      spectrum <- c(spectrum, subpeptide_mass)
    }
  }
  
  # Sort the spectrum
  spectrum <- sort(spectrum)
  
  return(spectrum)
}

# Alternative more efficient implementation
generate_spectrum_efficient <- function(peptide) {
  # Convert peptide to character vector
  peptide_chars <- unlist(strsplit(peptide, ""))
  
  # Get masses for each amino acid
  masses <- sapply(peptide_chars, function(aa) aa_masses[[aa]])
  
  # Calculate cumulative sums for efficient subpeptide mass calculation
  cumsum_masses <- c(0, cumsum(masses))
  
  # Generate all subpeptide masses
  spectrum <- c(0)  # Start with 0 (empty subpeptide)
  
  n <- length(masses)
  for (i in 1:n) {
    for (j in i:n) {
      # Calculate mass using cumulative sums: sum from i to j = cumsum[j] - cumsum[i-1]
      subpeptide_mass <- cumsum_masses[j + 1] - cumsum_masses[i]
      spectrum <- c(spectrum, subpeptide_mass)
    }
  }
  
  # Sort the spectrum
  spectrum <- sort(spectrum)
  
  return(spectrum)
}

# Example usage
peptide_example <- "SKEL"
result <- generate_spectrum_efficient(peptide_example)

# Display results
cat("Peptide:", peptide_example, "\n")
cat("Theoretical Spectrum:", paste(result, collapse = " "), "\n")
cat("Number of peaks:", length(result), "\n")

# Test with another example
peptide_example2 <- "NQV"
result2 <- generate_spectrum_efficient(peptide_example2)

cat("\nPeptide:", peptide_example2, "\n")
cat("Theoretical Spectrum:", paste(result2, collapse = " "), "\n")
cat("Number of peaks:", length(result2), "\n")

# Function to display spectrum in a formatted way
display_spectrum <- function(spectrum) {
  cat("Spectrum peaks (sorted): ", paste(spectrum, collapse = " "), "\n")
  cat("Total peaks:", length(spectrum), "\n")
  cat("Unique peaks:", length(unique(spectrum)), "\n")
}

# Display formatted results
cat("\n=== Formatted Results ===\n")
display_spectrum(result)
cat("\n")
display_spectrum(result2)
```

## Explanation

This R solution implements the theoretical spectrum generation for linear peptides with the following key components:

1. **Amino Acid Masses**: A lookup table containing the monoisotopic masses of 20 standard amino acids.

2. **Spectrum Generation Algorithm**:
   - Takes a peptide string as input
   - Converts each amino acid to its corresponding mass
   - Calculates all possible subpeptide masses by considering all contiguous subsequences
   - Includes the empty subpeptide (mass = 0) as the first element
   - Returns the sorted spectrum

3. **Efficiency Optimization**:
   - Uses cumulative sums to avoid recalculating subpeptide masses
   - Reduces time complexity from O(n³) to O(n²)
